1. What is CI/CD?
	â€¢	CI (Continuous Integration):
	â€¢	Developers frequently merge (integrate) their code into a shared repository (e.g., GitHub/GitLab).
	â€¢	Each integration triggers automated builds + tests.
	â€¢	Goal â†’ detect bugs early, keep codebase always working.
	â€¢	CD (Continuous Delivery):
	â€¢	Every change that passes CI is automatically prepared for release.
	â€¢	Deployment requires manual approval before pushing to production.
	â€¢	CD (Continuous Deployment):
	â€¢	Every change that passes CI automatically goes to production.
	â€¢	No human intervention. (Only rollback if something breaks).

ğŸ‘‰ Difference:
	â€¢	Delivery = Manual trigger to deploy
	â€¢	Deployment = Automatic trigger to deploy

â¸»

2. Why CI/CD is Important?
	â€¢	Faster development & release cycles.
	â€¢	Early bug detection.
	â€¢	Consistent builds (no â€œworks on my machineâ€ issue).
	â€¢	Reduced manual effort in deployment.
	â€¢	Reliable rollback strategies.

Big companies like Google, Netflix, Amazon deploy thousands of times per day using CI/CD.

â¸»

3. Pipeline Stages

A typical CI/CD pipeline looks like this:
	1.	Source Stage (Code Integration)
	â€¢	Code pushed â†’ triggers pipeline (GitHub Actions, Jenkins, GitLab CI, CircleCI).
	2.	Build Stage
	â€¢	Compile code (Java â†’ .jar, Node.js â†’ bundle, Python â†’ package).
	â€¢	Build Docker image.
	3.	Test Stage
	â€¢	Unit tests, integration tests, security scans, linting.
	4.	Artifact Stage
	â€¢	Store build in artifact repo (Nexus, JFrog Artifactory, S3, Docker Hub).
	5.	Deploy Stage
	â€¢	Deploy to staging â†’ run smoke tests.
	â€¢	Deploy to production (manual or automatic).
	6.	Monitor Stage
	â€¢	Logging, alerts, observability (Grafana, Prometheus, ELK).

